The Real Identity of the uploads/ Folder
The uploads/ folder on your computer is not a permanent gallery—it is a temporary bus stop.

Here is exactly what happens step-by-step when a user clicks "Submit" on your website:

The Arrival at the Bus Stop (Local File Creation):
Multer catches the incoming image from the internet, runs the security checks we talked about, and writes the file into your local uploads/ folder. If you open your code editor at this exact millisecond, yes, you will physically see the file sitting inside your local uploads/ folder.

The Uber Driver Picks It Up (Cloudinary Upload):
Your backend code then wakes up the Uber Driver (Cloudinary.uploader.upload) and hands them the file path pointing to that exact file inside your local uploads/ folder. The driver takes the file and drives it up to the Cloudinary cloud warehouse.

The Permanent Home (Cloudinary Storage):
Once the file arrives at Cloudinary, Cloudinary saves it permanently on their massive internet servers and hands you back that beautiful receipt URL (result.secure_url).

A Standard Professional Trick: Cleaning Up the Bus Stop
Right now, if you leave your code as it is, every single image your users upload will stay inside your local uploads/ folder forever and go to Cloudinary.

While this means you can view them locally, think about what happens when your platform grows: if 10,000 users upload 5MB images, your local server will completely run out of hard drive space and crash! Big tech companies don't keep files in two places at once.

To prevent this, professional engineers do a "clean up" step. Once the Uber driver successfully drops the file off at Cloudinary, they use a built-in Node.js tool called fs.unlinkSync() to delete the temporary file from the local uploads/ folder.

It looks like this in action:

JavaScript
const fs = require('fs'); // Node's built-in File System tool

const uploadToCloudinary = async (filePath) => {
    try {
        // 1. The driver takes the file from your local uploads/ folder to the cloud
        const result = await Cloudinary.uploader.upload(filePath);
        
        // 2. SUCCESS! The file is safe in the cloud. Delete the local temporary file!
        fs.unlinkSync(filePath); 
        
        return {
            url: result.secure_url,
            publicId: result.public_id
        }
    } catch (error) {
        // If the upload failed, we still want to remove the broken file from our local bus stop
        if (fs.existsSync(filePath)) {
            fs.unlinkSync(filePath);
        }
        throw error;
    }
}
